# {Your area} — {one-line definition}

> **This is a TEMPLATE.** Rename the directory and the file to remove the
> `_template_` prefix and `.template` suffix once you've filled it in:
> ```
> .claude/skills/_template_task_background/SKILL.md.template
>     →   .claude/skills/<your-task-name>/SKILL.md
> ```
> Claude Code only auto-loads files named exactly `SKILL.md` — the template
> filename is what keeps this from accidentally activating.

The agentic loop reloads this skill on every analyze and propose tick. Its
purpose is to encode the **non-obvious domain knowledge** that distinguishes
"someone who knows the field" from "someone who can read a paper". Anything
the agent could derive from a single textbook does NOT need to be in here;
the failure modes, the conventions, the things that trip up newcomers — those
do.

Canonical reference: cite the survey or textbook your subfield treats as
authoritative; keep the PDF at `references/<author-year>-survey.pdf` and use
short citation keys like `[A §3.1]` below.

